{
  "doc_id": "18830",
  "text": "The ombudsman ostensibly maintains sufficient distance from his own organizations' journalists, editors and owners in order to critique his colleagues, publicly sanction behavior, represent audience concerns and, most broadly, conscientiously reflect journalism's ideals [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] . He is not supposed to be an \"omniscient journalist\" who simply tells his colleagues should have been done, or lectures readers on how newspapers \"really\" work. Rather, he is often envisioned a \"privileged reader\" whose first mission is to critique the paper's integrity, examining his organization as an experienced outsider [CITATION_3] .",
